The soldiers themselves, among whom this sacrilegious plunder was distributed, received it with a bluss13 and, hardened as they were in acts of violence, they dreaded the just reproaches of their friends and relations. The procurator of Africa was a servant worthy of such a master, who considered the fines and confiscations of the rich as one* of the most fruitful branches of the Imperial revenue. An iniquitous sentence had been pronounced against some opulent youths of that country, the execution of which would have stripped them of far the greater part of their patrimony. In this extremity‚ a resolution that must either complete or prevent their ruin, was dictated by despair. A respite of three days, obtained with difficulty from the rapacious treasurer, was employed in collecting from their estates a great number of ssaves and peasants, blindly devoted to the com- mands of their lords, and armed with the rustic weapons of clubs and axes.
